cs.LG, cs.CV, cs.AI, cs.NE, cs.CL. 

The paper discusses an alternative approach to unsupervised feature learning that is based on continually accumulating features that make novel discriminations among the training set. This approach is not based on minimizing error and is inherently divergent instead of convergent. The paper demonstrates the quality of its learned features on the MNIST dataset. Given these characteristics, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper may also be relevant to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it discusses feature learning and discrimination in the context of neural networks.
